  "local_port": 55340,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What's the difference between a basic, intermediate and advanced WordPress website?",
  "response": "The level of a WordPress website\u2014basic, intermediate, or advanced\u2014is typically determined by its functionality, complexity, customization, and the skills required to build and maintain it. Here's a breakdown of the differences:\n\n---\n\n### **1. Basic WordPress Website**\n- **Purpose**: Simple websites for personal use, small businesses, or informational purposes.\n- **Features**:\n  - Limited number of pages (e.g., Home, About, Contact, Blog).\n  - Uses a pre-designed theme with minimal customization.\n  - Basic plugins for essential functions (e.g., contact form, SEO, caching).\n  - No custom coding or advanced features.\n  - Standard content types (posts, pages).\n- **Skills Required**:\n  - Familiarity with WordPress dashboard.\n  - Ability to install themes and plugins.\n  - Basic understanding of content creation and SEO.\n- **Examples**: Personal blogs, small business websites, portfolios.\n\n---\n\n### **2. Intermediate WordPress Website**\n- **Purpose**: More functionality and customization for growing businesses or specialized needs.\n- **Features**:\n  - Customized theme (child theme or minor CSS/HTML tweaks).\n  - Advanced plugins for e-commerce, membership, forums, etc. (e.g., WooCommerce, BuddyPress).\n  - Custom post types or taxonomies.\n  - Integration with third-party services (e.g., social media, payment gateways).\n  - Basic performance optimization (e.g., caching, image optimization).\n- **Skills Required**:\n  - Understanding of CSS, HTML, and basic PHP.\n  - Experience with plugin configuration and troubleshooting.\n  - Knowledge of site security and backup solutions.\n- **Examples**: Online stores, membership sites, small community forums.\n\n---\n\n### **3. Advanced WordPress Website**\n- **Purpose**: Highly customized, scalable, and feature-rich websites for large businesses or complex projects.\n- **Features**:\n  - Fully custom-built theme or heavily modified existing themes.\n  - Custom plugins or advanced plugin configurations.\n  - Complex functionality (e.g., API integrations, custom databases, multi-site setups).\n  - Advanced performance optimization (e.g., CDN, database optimization).\n  - Custom user roles and permissions.\n  - Advanced security measures (e.g., firewalls, two-factor authentication).\n- **Skills Required**:\n  - Strong knowledge of PHP, JavaScript, and WordPress core.\n  - Expertise in WordPress hooks, APIs, and database management.\n  - Experience with debugging and performance tuning.\n  - Ability to handle large-scale traffic and security threats.\n- **Examples**: Enterprise websites, SaaS platforms, large e-commerce stores, news portals.\n\n---\n\n### **Key Differences**\n| **Aspect**         | **Basic**                     | **Intermediate**                  | **Advanced**                     |\n|---------------------|-------------------------------|------------------------------------|----------------------------------|\n| **Customization**   | Minimal (pre-designed themes) | Moderate (tweaks and plugins)      | High (custom themes/plugins)     |\n| **Functionality**   | Simple (blog, static pages)   | Enhanced (e-commerce, memberships) | Complex (APIs, custom features) |\n| **Skills Required** | Beginner                     | Intermediate                       | Expert                           |\n| **Examples**        | Personal blog                | Small e-commerce store            | Enterprise platform              |\n\nBy understanding these levels, you can determine the scope of your project and the expertise needed to bring it to life.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
